body:
The following module verilates fine, works as expected:

```verilog
module InOutMod (input we, inout d);
  assign d = we ? 1'b1 : 1'bz;
endmodule
```

But put that bad boy inside an interface and we've got a bad time:

```verilog
interface InOutMod_if;
  wire we;
  wire d;

  modport ctrl(output we, inout d);
  modport prph(input we, inout d);
endinterface

module InOutMod(InOutMod_if.prph io_if);
  assign io_if.d = io_if.we ? 1'b1 : 1'bz;
endmodule

module InOutModWrap(input we, inout d);
  InOutMod_if io_if();
  assign io_if.we = we;
  assign io_if.d = d;

  InOutMod prph (.*);
endmodule
```
And we get:
```
Error-UNSUPPORTED: InOutMod.sv: Unsupported LHS tristate construct: VARXREF 'd'
```

We can swap the wrapper, make the interface version the wrapper of the explicitly enumerated ports version, and everything is peachy (other than losing some coverage). Still, seems silly that moving an `inout` from the module declaration into a modport breaks what is ostensibly a working simulation.

Happy to help with this if it seems feasible to fix without insane amounts of disruption. New to the verilator codebase so would appreciate pointers.

